DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain examines how traditions break down from within—through
internal contradictions, ossification, loss of rational
self-reflection, or disconnection between practice and theory.
MacIntyre's concept of epistemological crisis provides the
foundational framework: traditions fail when their conceptual
resources can no longer make sense of new challenges or when
internal incoherence undermines their ability to provide narrative
continuity. The literature reveals three primary failure modes:
(1) epistemological crisis when a tradition's scheme of belief
cannot account for novel situations; (2) ossification when living
practices decay into mere convention or ritual; and (3) loss of
practical wisdom (phronesis) when the capacity for sound judgment
within a tradition degenerates. Gadamer's hermeneutical approach
complements this by analyzing how prejudices can become rigid and
authoritative structures can lose their productive tension with
critical reason.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain directly addresses the core research question about
*how* traditions fail internally. Unlike external pressures
(domain 1), these are endogenous pathologies—traditions defeating
themselves through their own internal dynamics. MacIntyre's work
reveals that rational traditions can suffer epistemological crises
that they either successfully navigate (becoming stronger) or fail
to resolve (fragmenting or ossifying). This establishes criteria
for distinguishing healthy from pathological tradition evolution.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
The literature focuses heavily on epistemological aspects of
tradition failure but gives less attention to the concrete
mechanisms of practical degeneration—the day-to-day processes by
which living practices become dead rituals. There is also limited
empirical analysis of contemporary political traditions undergoing
epistemological crisis. Most examples are historical or religious
rather than political.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Organize around MacIntyre's epistemological crisis framework as the
central concept, then branch into specific failure mechanisms:
internal contradiction (Lutz, Herdt), ossification versus healthy
evolution (Angier, Lott), and phronesis decline (MacIntyre on
practices). Use Gadamer to analyze the role of prejudice and
authority in both enabling and constraining tradition rationality.
The synthesis should culminate in criteria for diagnosing tradition
pathology.

