  CORE ARGUMENT: Traces MacIntyre's intellectual journey from Marxism through epistemological crisis to Aristotelianism, analyzing how his own experience exemplifies tradition-constituted rationality and crisis resolution. MacIntyre's abandonment of Marxism resulted from recognizing its inability to provide coherent account of individual and common good or to resolve tensions between theory and practice. His turn to Aristotelian tradition resolved these crises by providing richer conceptual resources.

  RELEVANCE: Provides autobiographical case study of epistemological crisis and tradition transition. MacIntyre's own intellectual development illustrates the dynamics of tradition failure and reconstruction he theorizes. His experience shows how a tradition (Marxism) can fail to provide adequate account of fundamental questions (human telos, common good), precipitating crisis that requires moving to a different tradition with superior resources.

