  number = {3},
  pages = {319--335},
  doi = {10.1080/17450101.2019.1611015},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Whyte et al. argue that indigenous peoples have ancient
  traditions of environmental mobility, migration, and resettlement based on
  fluid, transformative relationships. Colonialism operates as a containment
  strategy that curtails indigenous mobility, disrupting these traditions by
  fixing populations in place and destroying adaptive capacity. The contemporary
  climate crisis and discussions of climate-induced resettlement must be
  understood in the context of ongoing colonial containment, not as genuinely
  "new" challenges. The authors analyze Gulf Coast and Alaskan cases to show
  how colonial restrictions on mobility compound climate vulnerability.

  RELEVANCE: Demonstrates concrete mechanism by which colonialism destroys
  traditions—not just through ideological delegitimation but through physical
  containment and prevention of traditional practices. Illuminates how external
