  disenchantment—democratic charisma generated through elections—can genuinely
  heal the spiritual deficit created by rationalization. Drawing on critiques
  by Storm (enchantment never fully vanished) and Marotta (demagification vs.
  disenchantment), Liu argues that democratic charisma remains structurally
  frail because it is embedded in the same legal-rational procedures that
  produce disenchantment. Electoral spectacles and populist appeals offer only
  transient simulations of meaning that are easily routinized or manipulated.

  RELEVANCE: Recent analysis (2025) of Weber's rationalization thesis and its
  implications for tradition and meaning in modernity. Relevant for understanding
  limits of procedural solutions to tradition breakdown—shows how formal
  democratic procedures cannot restore the embedded meaning that traditional
  structures provided. Illuminates tension between efficient governance (requiring
  rationalization) and authentic collective belief (requiring tradition or
  charisma).

  POSITION: Neo-Weberian critique; skeptical of democratic proceduralism as
  response to disenchantment. Emphasizes structural contradictions in modern
  attempts to generate meaning through rationalized institutions.
  },
  keywords = {Weber, disenchantment, democracy, High}
}

@book{taylor1990sources,
