  transformations in moral frameworks from Plato through Romanticism. He argues
  that modern identity is shaped by three major cultural shifts: internalization
  of moral sources, affirmation of ordinary life, and expressivist turn toward
  authenticity. These shifts create distinctively modern moral horizons but also
  generate characteristic pathologies including instrumental reason's dominance
  and loss of transcendent frameworks.

  RELEVANCE: Foundational work on how modernization transforms the self's
  relationship to tradition and moral authority. Shows how shift from external
  traditional sources to internal authenticity undermines traditions' authority
  by relocating moral sources within the individual. The internalization Taylor
  describes creates structural conditions where tradition appears as external
  imposition rather than constitutive framework. Links directly to tradition
  breakdown through transformation of moral epistemology.

  POSITION: Communitarian-influenced but not anti-modern; seeks to recover
  moral sources compatible with modernity. Critical of procedural liberalism
  but not nostalgic for pre-modern frameworks.
  },
  keywords = {modern-identity, moral-sources, authenticity, High}
}

@article{ali2022modernity,
