  year = {2017},
  volume = {17},
  number = {1},
  pages = {24--47},
  doi = {10.15543/MWS/2017/1/4},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Schluchter distinguishes Weber's concept of disenchantment
  from standard secularization theses, showing Weber's usage encompasses both
  religious and scientific disenchantment in dialectical relationship. He
  compares Weber's framework with Charles Taylor's A Secular Age, noting both
  convergences and divergences. Weber attributed broader meaning to disenchantment
  by distinguishing types and showing their historical interaction with
  reenchantment processes. Both authors conclude that even in secular age religion
  persists but religious commitment becomes optional, fundamentally changing
  religious situation in modernity.

  RELEVANCE: Clarifies Weber's disenchantment thesis and its relationship to
  tradition breakdown through rationalization. Shows disenchantment operates
  dialectically—religious rationalization (Protestant Reformation) enabled
  scientific rationalization which then undermined religious tradition. Important
  for understanding how tradition breakdown can be inadvertently caused by
  tradition-internal reform movements (connects to internal breakdown mechanisms).
  Illuminates philosophical foundations of secularization theory.

  POSITION: Neo-Weberian; emphasizes complexity and dialectics of rationalization
