  RELEVANCE: Recent (2024) application of Hayek's constructivism critique to
  contemporary cultural change, showing continuity of rationalism critique into
  present. Relevant for understanding how tradition breakdown through deliberate
  reconstruction threatens spontaneous order theorists value. Illustrates tension
  between defending traditional liberal order and avoiding reactionary cultural
  politics. Shows how external pressure of "constructivist" cultural movements
  can threaten evolved traditional institutions.

  POSITION: Hayekian libertarianism; culturally conservative regarding
  spontaneous order. Opposes both state intervention and cultural constructivism.
  },
  keywords = {Hayek, spontaneous-order, constructivism, Medium}
}

@article{piccolo2023critical,
  author = {Piccolo, Samuel},
  title = {Critical Theory and North American Indigenous Thought},
  journal = {European Journal of Political Theory},
  year = {2023},
  volume = {23},
  number = {3},
  pages = {545--566},
  doi = {10.1177/14748851231177171},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Piccolo argues that recent efforts to "decolonize critical
  theory" by Amy Allen and Robert Nichols fail to consider two key elements'
  relationship with Indigenous thought: (1) all normativity is generated
  immanently from historically/socially located struggle; (2) normativity is
